<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[192,1440,781,870]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,333,781,805]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[444,745,781,805]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustomarginata">
<emphasis box="[444,745,781,805]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Beltia angustomarginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by the wide pronotum and “arrowhead”- shaped apex of the median lobe. Females have a less obviously transverse pronotum, but share with the male a strong purple reflex on the upper body.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[192,1440,893,1109]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,323,893,917]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bechyne, J." box="[330,518,893,917]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="26 - 303" refId="ref24974" refString="Bechyne, J. 1953. Katalog der neotropischen eumolpiden (Col. Phytoph. Chrysomeloidea). Entomologische Arbeiten aus dem Museum G. Frey 4: 26 - 303." type="journal article" year="1953">Bechynĕ (1953)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[649,909,893,916]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustomarginata">
<emphasis box="[649,909,893,916]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">B. angustomarginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName box="[1139,1284,893,917]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Colaspoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1139,1284,893,917]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Colaspoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(now 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[1358,1431,893,917]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1358,1431,893,917]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
<taxonomicName box="[192,308,925,949]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Colaspoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="placidula">
<emphasis box="[192,308,925,949]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">placidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is so far known only from a small area of 
<collectingCountry box="[909,971,926,949]" name="Peru" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Peru</collectingCountry>
, based on a narrower pronotal margin and deeper postbasal depression. The structure and punctation of the pronotum in these two forms are different; additionally, in all specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[754,904,989,1013]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Colaspoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="placidula">
<emphasis box="[754,904,989,1013]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">B. placidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the legs are entirely dark fulvous to brown, whereas all known specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[589,848,1021,1044]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustomarginata">
<emphasis box="[589,848,1021,1044]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">B. angustomarginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have metallic legs. This, along with the fact that both forms seem to have limited and disjunct distributions, appears to me to justify considering them distinct species. So far, this species (including the 
<typeStatus box="[774,826,1085,1109]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">type</typeStatus>
) has been collected only in central 
<collectingCountry box="[1230,1330,1086,1109]" name="Panama" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Panama</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1344,1427,1085,1109]" captionStart="Figures 80–82" captionStartId="44.[192,286,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[203,1427,215,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[203,1429,211,1815]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="Figures 80–82. Distribution maps for Beltia spp.: Nicaragua, Costa Rica, and Panama. 80) Beltia angustomarginata (squares), B. osa (triangles), B. vacilona (circles). 81) Beltia chiriquensis (circles), B. herreri (stars), B. nicaraguensis (hexagons). 82) Beltia sanchezae (square), B. tilarana (inverted triangles), B. tisingalita (stars)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713529" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713529/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
